-- French Stocks: Aeroports de Paris, Air France, Carrefour, Nexans, PPR Move
-- B y   A d a m   E w i n g
-- 2010-10-18T16:09:33Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-18/air-france-total-edf-adp-jcdecaux-thermador-french-equity-preview.html
France’s CAC 40 Index rose 0.2
percent to 3,834.5 at the 5:30 p.m. close in Paris, the highest
level since April. The SBF 120 Index gained 0.2 percent to
2,857.89.  The following shares rose or fell in Paris. Stock symbols
are in parentheses.  Aeroports de Paris SA  (ADP FP), the operator of the French
capital’s Charles de Gaulle and Orly airports, fell 2.1 percent
to 62.05 euros. French truckers blocked highways and officials
deployed police to prevent strikers from cutting fuel supplies
as the standoff hardened over President Nicolas Sarkozy’s plans
to raise the retirement age to 62.  Air France-KLM Group  (AF FP) rose 3.9 percent to 12.66
euros, the highest price since April. France’s largest airline
was raised to “buy” from “hold” at Citigroup Inc.  Carrefour SA  (CA FP) slipped 1 percent to 38.11 euros,
extending the 4.1 percent slide on Oct. 15. The world’s second-
largest retailer was cut to “hold” from “buy” at Citigroup.  Nexans SA  (NEX FP) jumped 2.3 percent to 54.36 euros,
rebounding from the 1.7 percent slump on Oct. 15. The world’s
biggest maker of cables and wires said it’s planning a takeover
bid for Draka Holding NV that values its Dutch rival at 731
million euros ($1 billion).  PPR SA  (PP FP) slumped 2.8 percent to 115.90 euros, its
biggest drop in two months. The owner of the Fnac retail chain
was cut to “sell” from “hold” at Deutsche Bank AG, which said
“the Gucci brand is continuing to underperform relative to its
peers in terms of sales growth, profits growth and margins.”  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Adam Ewing  in Stockholm at 
 aewing5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
David Merritt at 
 dmerritt1@bloomberg.net . 